<subSubSection id="BBFC65209524FFD8FF1F5F9CFD7F7F17" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="F35936AB9524FFD8FF1F5F9CFE3E7F47" blockId="50.[151,1437,402,708]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis id="C192EAB99524FFD8FF1F5F9CFEC37CCF" bold="true" box="[151,279,402,428]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Tube from pale pink to salmon, with prominent longitudinal ridge, forming crest, lacking peristomes or alveoli. Opercular peduncle with wide wings. Operculum with up to five successive calcareous plates, becoming progressively smaller toward apex (
<figureCitation id="6BDD2A2E9524FFD8FC8C5FECFCA57C9F" box="[772,881,482,508]" captionStart="FIGURE 13" captionStartId="51.[151,255,1902,1926]" captionTargetBox="[263,1320,187,1871]" captionTargetId="figure-62@51.[228,1358,184,1878]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="FIGURE 13. A: Spirobranchus latiscapus, from Hawaii. A, operculum, lateral view. B–C: Spirobranchus spinosus, from California, USNM 17109, holotype. B–C, operculum, aboral and lateral views. D: Vermiliopsis infundibulum/glandigera complex, from Baja California Sur, UANL 365. D, operculum, lateral view. (Fig. A, redrawn from Bailey-Brock, 1972)." pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Fig. 13A</figureCitation>
). Collar with “ 
<taxonomicName id="34E64D289524FFD8FB945FECFB137C98" authorityName="de Blainville" authorityYear="1818" box="[1052,1223,482,507]" class="Polychaeta" family="Serpulidae" genus="Spirobranchus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Sabellida" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Annelida" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="C192EAB99524FFD8FB945FECFB137C98" box="[1052,1223,482,507]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Spirobranchus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
” chaetae coarsely serrated in subapical section.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F35936AB9524FFD8FF4E5C3CFD7F7F17" blockId="50.[151,1437,402,708]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis id="C192EAB99524FFD8FF4E5C3CFEF97F2F" bold="true" box="[198,301,562,588]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Habitat.</emphasis>
Depth: 
<quantity id="341E9B4E9524FFD8FE075C3CFDDE7F2F" box="[399,522,562,588]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.175" metricValueMax="6.0" metricValueMin="0.35" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" unit="m" value="317.5" valueMax="600.0" valueMin="35.0">
35– 
<specimenCount id="E5E0FD229524FFD8FE335C3CFDDE7F2F" box="[443,522,562,588]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="generic">600 m</specimenCount>
</quantity>
. On gastropod shells of 
<taxonomicName id="34E64D289524FFD8FCA65C3CFBD47F28" box="[814,1024,562,587]" class="Gastropoda" family="Xenophoridae" genus="Xenophora" kingdom="Animalia" order="Littorinimorpha" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="tenuis">
<emphasis id="C192EAB99524FFD8FCA65C3CFBD47F28" box="[814,1024,562,587]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Xenophora tenuis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, on precious pink coral 
<taxonomicName id="34E64D289524FFD8FAAB5C3CFED87F10" baseAuthorityName="Dana" baseAuthorityYear="1846" class="Anthozoa" family="Coralliidae" genus="Corallium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Alcyonacea" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="secundum">
<emphasis id="C192EAB99524FFD8FAAB5C3CFED87F10" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Corallium secundum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and on solitary coral 
<emphasis id="C192EAB99524FFD8FD835C54FD577F10" box="[523,643,602,627]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Cyatheras</emphasis>
sp.
</paragraph>
